              <b>
               x
              </b>
              and
              <b>
               y
              </b>
              will have the same number of elements.
             </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
             <td align="center" class="statText" valign="top">
              -
             </td>
             <td class="statText">
              <b>
               x
              </b>
              will have between 3 and 50 elements inclusive.
             </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
             <td align="center" class="statText" valign="top">
              -
             </td>
             <td class="statText">
              <b>
               y
              </b>
              will have between 3 and 50 elements inclusive.
             </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
             <td align="center" class="statText" valign="top">
              -
             </td>
             <td class="statText">
              each element in
              <b>
               x
              </b>
              will be between -10000 and 10000 inclusive.
             </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
             <td align="center" class="statText" valign="top">
              -
             </td>
             <td class="statText">
              each element in
              <b>
               y
              </b>
              will be between -10000 and 10000 inclusive.
             </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
             <td align="center" class="statText" valign="top">
              -
             </td>
             <td class="statText">
